The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into the negative against the close of business.
After the steep decline in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ’s shares accounted for almost half of normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange followed up on Monday’s slump right at the start of Tuesday’s deals, when it fell a further six percentage points.
This time the reason for the break-in was Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the market’s reaction to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilization plan for the financial sector there, is thus evident.
Fall of shares in Asia
Shares on the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index lost nearly four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was later able to make up for some of the losses, reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while the markets in Shanghai were closed.
Stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then decreased losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent according to the index there.
“The timing for the bailout in the U.S. is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide,” said Hong Kong’s head of monetary affairs, Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass the draft to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries would also be affected by the burglary.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, which would cost up to $700 billion (nearly K<0xC4><0x8D> 12 trillion).
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the major stock indices recorded the largest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by almost seven percent, a similar slump it had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there were hardly any signs that the draft would not come through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: US government can pump $700 billion into the banks
The top representatives of the US Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance to the American financial system.
This is to be voted on at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a breakthrough in talks to pass a $700 billion bailout plan in the form of financial assistance to the U.S. financial system (about CZK 12 trillion).
However, this does not mean victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the U.S. Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, Chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee Barney Frank told Reuters.
In the Senate, according to various sources, the plan could probably be voted on on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a communication on the plan’s adoption should be the first significant psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
After that, however, there is a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms of how to help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our divergent views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like,” said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat.
According to her, a final vote could take place on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final shape.
This provides for the purchase of unsold mortgage assets from the financial companies, which plunge the financial companies into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must be effective in the market.
You have to continue the recovery plan, but I think we’re on target,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian businesses
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
Nevada Senator Harry Reid said lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
This is to reassure investors of deals on the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision by Congress could affect the business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not entirely clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and it is unclear whether the negotiations could still fail at the last minute due to a problem.
Legislators hope it will be passed in the next few days.
However, the law will undergo some changes.
The total amount intended to help the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be provided as soon as possible, as President George Bush called for.
But Congress can block the distribution of the remaining money if it feels that the program is not performing its function, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush sees progress in negotiations as positive
While the president has veto power in this decision, Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was based on obtaining finances to buy bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen, has persisted because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
“We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, then the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The American President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "appreciated the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing benefits, and a timetable for funding the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the program and sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
The Ministry of Finance is to lead it.
“We’ve worked very hard on this and made great progress toward an agreement that works and is important to the market and to all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who are having trouble repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages it buys up, with the goal being to lower the monthly costs for the debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to Patria Finance Chief Economist David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
“It’s because you don’t know the mechanism by which and at what price the problematic assets are bought.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government split the losses between each other,” Marek told iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week is, in Marek’s view, not decisive.
“Much more important is for Congressmen to agree to support the plan and say goodbye to it as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement on the adoption is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
Duel on knife edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost any mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls yet.
So, of course, it looks like it’s better to just buy a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons why you should buy an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
Surely it is hard to buy a great expensive turntable at home to listen to the latest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical innovations do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably dream at least of one.
This is also the case with music when traveling, i.e. with compressed music, in simplified terms - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink Floyd fan will probably hardly be able to cope with headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some good music players can play a lot more than just music, but what phones can do, they don’t even hint at.
No modern device can be used as universally as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions, the calling and the texting, it can play music and videos, record both, it has sometimes a better, sometimes a worse camera and can maybe also navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph.
But the universality of mobile phones also comes with disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will have to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Only a few phones can play music for more than ten-twelve hours, most of the time it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
That’s why you should expect the cheap phones to not be able to play music for more than a few hours.
If you then still make calls from time to time, you prefer to buy a charger for the office - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you will not have this problem, even the less good will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one time charging off.
Another problem is when you want to transfer the music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB termination, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can do without reduction with the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones.
With players, you don’t need any special software, except for the iPod.
You only need to feed the device with music from your PC via USB port.
Most mobile phones and players create their own music library, arranged according to the name of the artist, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating by users.
Some devices only map the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should especially inquire about the battery life, storage capacity, quality and type of sound and, of course, the ease of use.
If music is primarily a backdrop for you and you listen to it every day only briefly, for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
This is something almost every cell phone can do.
You also don’t have to control which music formats a mobile phone or player can handle.
MP3 create all of them, and most of the music you get will just be in this format.
The format is one of the most widely used, and besides, most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online.
You only need to go to the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile internet, and you can buy a song or album.
This service can in and of itself be a compelling argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of sales of music (be it via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones with them.
If you feel like listening to something, reach for the phone in the jacket pocket while the player is at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device with you.
If not, you can fall back on the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music mobile phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you already get a very decent Walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5 mm aperture for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players is in the ease of use.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - player can really serve anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the formerly normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of a mistakenly employed mobile internet and a subsequently horrendous bill for data transmissions.
Which device should you now reach for
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But beware.
In the basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are usually supported.
Only the most expensive can read 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, then you can reach for Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, you prefer to take specialized phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
The Sony Ericsson is farthest away, whose Walkman series phones have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price range of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) afford you MP3 players of the above manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Perhaps it will not be long in coming.
That the Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
Incidentally, this was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which drew attention to the fact that the price for an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, it is so likely to come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks competition, which really makes a challenge.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain about the fact that there is an extreme amount of competition on the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, who had often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, agrees with this.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies anymore).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual providers into the mobile communications market in particular brought with it a significant price reduction, to which the traditional mobile communications providers then also had to react.
Even before companies such as Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
But it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you do not have to look for examples for a long time.
In February of this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in attracting more than 100 thousand customers, making it the fifth largest provider in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
They do not require a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually distinguish themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but this is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-cliche target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
The spokesperson for Vodafone Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile phone providers mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking is more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," says Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, press officer of the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything in their power to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in starting a virtual mobile service provider has long been demonstrated by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, press spokesman for the group.
Maybe there will be better times.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a fully-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on."
She adds: “There will be hardly any virtual provider on T-Mobile’s network by the end of the year.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think so short-term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we regard as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet.”
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should it be easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
That the providers can pull together when it comes to something, also proves the long back and forth around the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was exerted by T-Mobile when U:fon was launched.
This is also proven by the publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
Now, however, U:fon is particularly suitable as an argument for why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile communications market was recently strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile communications provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, who unfortunately - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - do not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, related to this entire problem his very typical attitude.
“The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider via the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers", said in his response to our request Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Such a formulation would not come as a surprise to representatives of the providers.
This is more than worrying by an authority that is supposed to represent consumer interests and, among other things, ensure that no one abuses its position in the market.
In particular, when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Foreigners, where virtual providers operate normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
But probably the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction do not belong to the interests of the OHS.
What is truly shocking in this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile service providers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same price of petrol at petrol stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not detected any sign of anti-competitive action in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also lacking for the regulator of telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, elaborated by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile service providers holds a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily occupies a dominant position in a certain segment.
Even if you do not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile phone providers are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, it has not been possible to enforce the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one is looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partly public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile telephone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which may lead to an end of cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not get around among those responsible for the mobile service providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
The activities of these companies provide them with not negligible profits, at the same time they are - in contrast to the actual virtual providers - not impaired by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all this, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot have it fully as the normal customers of the mobile service providers."
But that alone should at least seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile service providers close their eyes to such an approach, why do they block themselves against a virtual provider?
It must be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the provider’s statement that they know nothing about it and their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasised several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought with it a significant drop in the price of the various services.
Virtually in all countries where virtual providers have emerged, traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely in these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, which by no means tried to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Be it through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator, and this was followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies throw themselves into the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competences in these cases is more than favorable.
But let’s not throw the gun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will then finally make no more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
