The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the US
The Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be a part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans are said to have turned to the US President in 1945.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and that is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
In the letter, the Germans from Krumau ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was captured by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," read a letter signed with the words "people for whom the fate of the Sudeten lies at the heart."
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia suggests to the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national character - that they would expect brutality, recklessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protection of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are ascribing this area to a foreign state which has tried to suppress and eliminate minorities and has contributed nothing at all to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors are unable to sign is allegedly the fear of revenge from the “Czech oppressors”.
If the US President has doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest region on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the US or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat na<0xC3><0xAF>ve in today's knowledge of post-war history, according to some contemporary witnesses it paints a good picture with regard to the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans had to at least suspect that they would negotiate their deportation from the republic, only a few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Still others believed they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was used in the war as a Budweiser German in the Navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he was taken into British captivity at the end of the war and taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would suit them," Chalupa said.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected him to be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> decrees.
