Sleepless nights for creditors of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, said German Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück only last week.
How good that the politician used the word "relative" and also interwoven that the German banking sector is not spared from the crisis-prone developments.
Because it happened this weekend.
Munich-based real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), listed in the Dax, receives a billion-dollar loan from a consortium of German banks in order to shield itself from the turbulence in the markets.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan assistance amounted to up to 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate only has to pay interest on the part it claims.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
The background is losses to the daughter Depfa.
According to a newspaper report for long-term projects for which he has loaned money, the state financier had refinanced himself extremely short-term - which is no longer possible because of the distrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s cash reserve had shrunk by 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, and the equity ratio had also declined slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net income from financial activities fell to zero compared to the same period of the previous year, while income from attributions to receivables and certain securities and from the reversal of provisions in the credit business fell by more than 70 percent to EUR 5 million.
Only thanks to higher income from reimbursements of downstream transfer costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group as well as from the reimbursement of interest according to the tax regulations and from the business procurement for Group companies, the decline in earnings was still moderate at around 16 percent.
The former state financier had speculated after its privatization in 1990 first with commercial real estate loans, which had then been spun off in the Aareal Bank.
Because they earned too little in traditional state financing, the Depfa had then become increasingly involved in infrastructure projects and the financing of joint projects of private investors and the state (Private Public Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, the Hypo Real Estate must now make depreciations that will have a "substantial material effect" on the profit and loss account of the group, it is said to be quite indefinite.
The fact is that the dividend has been cancelled.
In 2007, it was cut by two-thirds.
Hypo Real Estate has been a major state and infrastructure financier since the acquisition of Depfa.
It is more dependent than other institutions on refinancing in the interbank market because it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the American investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending among the banks has largely dried up again, as the banks hoard their liquidity.
Every year, Hypo Real Estate needs short-term funding to refinance part of Depfa’s loan portfolio – around EUR 50 billion.
According to Hypo Real Estate, the financing needs of the group are covered by the loan for the foreseeable future and the company is "shielded from the influence of the currently largely inoperable international money markets".
From other sources, it can be heard that thanks to the funds, the refinancing was secured until the end of 2009.
HRE CEO Georg Funke said that the Hypo Real Estate Group will no longer have to use the money markets for the foreseeable future.
The Bundesbank and the Bundesanstalt für Finanzdienstleistungsaufsicht (BaFin) assume that the marketability of the Hypo Real Estate Group is now secured.
This is to be hoped for by shareholders and creditors of the bank.
But given the dynamics and uncertainties of the crisis, there is probably no certainty.
In fact, it is not inconceivable that the financing does not have to be used to its full extent.
But also the opposite is not to be worn out.
Since the bank was reportedly still facing insolvency on late Sunday evening, even the at least temporary rescue is not able to calm the minds.
The share price plunges by 75 percent to EUR 3.30.
On the other hand, bond prices hold up quite well.
While the senior debt hardly shows any movement, the prices of subordinated bonds give off more clearly.
Above all, the bonds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and, understandably, the maturities beyond 2009 are affected.
If Hypo-Real-Estate-Bonds once appeared as a speculative investment alternative, then after the significant worsening of the banking crisis and the institution itself, which had only brought the crisis into its own hands with the takeover of the Depfa, its value must be regarded as dependent on the stability of the international financial system.
As long as central banks, governments and less distressed commercial banks are ready to support the system, it can be assumed that pensions will be paid out on time.
Or something that hardly anyone dares to hope for at the moment – that the financial crisis will be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in view of the reports that are sweeping over with the partial nationalization, the probability that borders on security has currently become only a legitimate hope.
This should prepare especially long-term believers some sleepless nights with the decision whether they should part with their engagements.
After all, short-term investors can use a closing line to make a loss carry forward for future withholding tax payments on price gains of later years.
