SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far where we can not even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it poses dead, flees, or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and in the execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So, at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: Since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, however it may be, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially using the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts more to the neural correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the emergence of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I attribute it to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of the brain’s localized defense system (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies working memory.
Seen in this way, sensations are closely tied to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and, in particular, humans.
In combination with the linguistic nature, there are subtle gradations of feeling, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the cortex and brainstem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-genre sensations.
Theoretically, I cannot disagree with this, but I think it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what seems like fear in rats and humans probably feels the same in both cases: but how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same if they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees in danger if it also feels fear?
In my view, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove an equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brainstem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it for humans, how would you prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and on language), I’d rather explore the emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress on the neural level beckons here, provided one measures the same in rats and humans.
Just as I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, nor do I explore sensations, I do not know whether they exist.
You might think that’s short-sighted, but I’d rather go ahead than run into a wall all the time.
I am a practical emotionalist.
