“Very little space has remained in the city’s possession and we want Extra Place to continue to belong to the city,” she said.
"There could be offers on how to repair and operate the road, which could be done by Avalon, but we also want public access to be guaranteed."
Avalon Bay announced a few months ago that it would re-pave the small street and set up seats that would include a café to which the company would like to rent out space.
The idea that Avalon Bay could buy the road was made public for the first time during the meeting this month.
Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said that while the company wanted to use the road, it did not necessarily want to own it.
“Avalon Bay’s main concern is to renovate this dilapidated alley and make it a public meeting place,” she said, adding that the city itself had proposed the sale.
Seth Donlin, spokesman for the Department of Building Protection, said it was indeed the city’s desire to sell the street, stressing that the department’s job was to develop the properties rather than manage them.
Compared to its colorful neighborhood of The Bowery, Extra Place has retained some of its historical impression.
Some believe the road got its name in 1802, when a large farm owned by Philip Minthorne was divided among his numerous children and a narrow strip of land was claimed by none.
The back door of the CBGB music club, the punk rock monument that closed in 2006, opened to the Extra Place and the street is certainly best known as the backdrop for the photo on the cover of Ramones' "Rocket to Russia" album.
The patch was great, said Danny Fields, the manager of the Ramones, who took the photo in November 1976.
The road was full of scrap, rags and parts of barrels, posters, leaves and ropes.
Some residents, including the bloggers who write about the gentrification of the East Village, have rejected the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that this public property, as modest as it is, should remain public.
Others have hailed Extra Place as a rarity – a virtually unchanged fragment of the city that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs the blog called "Jeremiah's Disappearing New York" (subtitled "The Book of Complaints: A Bitter Nostalgic Look at the Extinct City"), has published part of the city's history talk about Extra Place, which appeared in The New Yorker magazine in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote at the time: “Extra Place is a small narrow cul-de-sac that remains dark even during the day and is characterized by rusted metal doors of warehouses, locked windows and week-old newspapers flying past gutters.”
With a few exceptions, the street has looked just as recently on one evening.
A rat ran through the back of the street, not far from the door that used to lead to the CBGB, where today there is a more expensive clothing store.
Graffiti could be seen on the walls and an empty beer bottle lay on the floor not far from a fresh bundle of discarded newspapers.
Some passersby said they had rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested that the road could be polished up a bit.
Fields added that in his opinion, some people underestimate the appeal of the road in its current state.
The best years of my life, he said, were in the places that were dark, damp, and disgusting.
Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates’ positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior research fellow in California Studies and senior director in the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice."
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the likelihood of African-American and Hispanic students successfully completing school is lower than that of white students” — which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition period in education for those who are just learning English.
Still, the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently arrived in the country, are learning English.
Nevertheless, in 2008 an astonishing 100 percent of fourth grade students passed the state exam in maths at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This amazing success has been achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
The Sixth Street School focuses on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
The school also practices the approach of training in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should pay attention to, according to headmaster Linda Mikels.
This approach places emphasis on the almost exclusive use of the English language in subject teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. 12 months later you would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize him.
“It works,” she noted, “it works for us.”
Would Obama use a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large proportion of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within its own party (the national image associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While agreeing to the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation targeting “English only.”
Instead, he said, “You should make sure your child can speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close the performance gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work, rather than despising and trivializing them.
Oil prices fall as a result of renewed fears about the economy
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday due to fears that even the American bailout plan for the financial markets might not be enough to revive the economy.
Crude futures on the New York Stock Exchange fell 7 percent in the morning session to $99.80 per barrel.
Since last Monday, the price has fallen by more than $20.
Over the past two weeks, commodity markets have been rocked by both the financial turmoil on Wall Street and strong hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After prices peaked at $145.29 per barrel in July, they fell to nearly $90 per barrel this month, only to rise again as a result of the huge uncertainty in financial markets.
On Monday, investors expressed concern again, even though congressional representatives had announced they had agreed on a rescue plan over the weekend, which was to be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis was far from over.
In the final chapter of the growing crisis, according to a government statement on Monday, Citigroup is to buy up the banking business of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalized the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a rescue plan, it seems that it has not been possible to revive the mood in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, demand for goods, including oil, is expected to continue to decline.
Analysts at Deutsche Bank have written in a message to investors that the forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates have become extremely uncertain.
We believe, they write further, that the goods markets will also be affected.
“From the perspective of commodity markets, we are most concerned about whether the U.S. American virus is spreading worldwide, especially to China.”
The bank’s analysts have revised down their expectations for oil consumption due to weak economic growth for the coming year, and lowered their oil and gas price forecasts for 2009 by 20%.
Team record set by series in second quarter
Center-back Shaun Ellis thought he’d seen it all after hitting the Jets jersey more often than anyone else for the last eight and a half years.
Then, on Sunday, he saw the second quarter, in which the Jets turned an unsuccessful game into a triumphal procession.
“I’ve never seen anything like it,” Ellis said.
After a sloppy game between the Jets and the Arizona Cardinals that matched the bad weather, the second quarter began.
However, when quarterback Brett Favre’s pass arrived at Lavernue’s Coles for a 12-yard touchdown, that marked the perfect prelude to an afternoon when their evolving collaboration took a giant step forward.
Favre found Coles in this quarter for two more touchdowns, one slipping as an outside defender and the other 10 seconds before the end of the half.
“I didn’t put in a lot of effort,” Coles says about the passes that went to Coles.
"He's a super player.
We voted no matter what people think.”
While Favre and Cole were playing catch, defense quarterback Kurt Warner took apart.
Full-back Darrelle Revis intercepted an injured throw and turned it into a 32-yard touchdown.
Libero Erik Smith came to another pass and intercepted it.
Linebacker David Bowens then caused a loss to Warner.
The last ball loss, forced at Bowens, was probably the craziest.
The Cardinals had captured the ball with 10 seconds left in the game when the Jets retook the ball and Jay Feely turned a 20 yard shot to 34-0 lead.
That was the most points the Jets had ever scored in a quarter.
