A lot of points were scored in a short period of time."
Retired Gebrselassie beats his world record
Haile Gebrselassie from Ethiopia has once again shown why some consider him to be the best long-distance runner of all time, after breaking his own record in the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to make the 42.2-kilometer race in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous result of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has thus set his 26th world record in his versatile career, in which he has achieved at least one world championship title or set a world record on every track from one kilometre to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon for fear that, in retrospect, the air pollution could exacerbate his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions - in the sun and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won with an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since track runners such as Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya switched to long-distance races, the record time for marathon in the last 10 years has fallen by more than 2 minutes, since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won in 1998 in Berlin with the result 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and therefore could not train for a week.
Obviously, he came back refreshed after a break and not rusted up.
“I’m so happy,” he told reporters.
"Everything went perfectly.
I resumed training a week ago and still had some concerns today, but in the end it was all great."
He has been criticized - especially in Kenya, Ethiopia's rival from East Africa - for orchestrating his races excessively, avoiding many of the world's best marathon stars in general, relying too much on the race leaders as if it were a track race, and setting world records above the competition.
But this criticism hardly harms the size of Gebrselassie as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the centre of the track in 1:02:04.
Two elite runners from Kenya, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, have continued to challenge Gebrselassie after the pacemakers had slowed down.
A little more than three miles before the finish, Gebrselassie made his last appearance to break away from Kwambai, who came in second in 2:05:36, improving his best time by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
For women, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now German, has completed a remarkable year by showing the seventh fastest result of all time with 2:19:19.
The world record of 2:15:25 is held by Paul Radcliff from Great Britain.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko surprisingly won the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games due to problems described as a back injury, but recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She skilfully planned her run by having a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners pulled out at first, but overtook after 30 kilometers.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia came in second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop from Kenya came in third in 2:25:01.
The pride and hardships in the lives of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Tucked away among the excesses of Orlando’s theme parks, a few miles from the glittering, loud, and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture emerge.
Eatonville, the first entirely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet places, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city that describes it – and that made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida Travel Guide, produced by the Federal Writers’ Project at the time of the Depression – is and remains a place of the very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation about race relations, many here continue to be fed up with being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and parishioner of the city's oldest church.
It has to be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and on guard.
And so right the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida tour guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Impudent as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"Off the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always cares about, though he can hardly read or write."
She also mentioned Dash's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sold drinks of any kind and whatever-fits-on-hours rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls Hurston immortalized, citing the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual innuendo.
She added, “Some people didn’t like this.”
Hurtson is still remembered as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came rushing into town, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in trousers, in a city that even today imagines something of her venerable style of dress.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, whereas many despised them.
"People were always glad to see Zora," said Mr. Franklin.
But “she never stayed too long,” he added as he rocked in his chair, on a rear-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no large memorial service, no large-scale public readings.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their heritage in the least," said Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial miscegenation brought hatred to the community.
"In that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away," Mr. Franklin said.
“There was once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand for integration, calling its decision in the Brown case against the school board "offensive rather than respecting my race."
Residents today say that although the lifting of racial segregation has been positive in some respects, it has weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
“Black kids were used to being hugged — I remember — hugging their teacher in the morning and hugging their teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group for the protection of the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students stopped coming from the same place.
"You didn't hug his white teacher, because he was a white teacher - I mean there is a cultural divide," Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors and artists who defied prejudice, as they did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's unnamed grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-praised Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was to be found on the bookshelves, and again made it part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway enlivened the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, aroused genuine citizen pride," Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city’s self-image.
There were more and more arrivals, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-appreciate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Historic Register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a specialty in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It’s 90% black these days.)
Outsiders in search of Eatonville's history and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, a permit is required in advance and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men working in the field - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Mrs. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a penchant for dark red, still fear that her shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival was getting bigger, an increased degree of home pride was also born.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and hardworking, silly and mixed up as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or with the police, who he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to properly describe Eatonville.
“Most people who just drive through here will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’ ” Alondra Kenon said the other day on a Sunday after church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
Here in New York, people speak fluent financial Latin.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspaper stands and the massive television screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t even realize they were in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York, daily have the worst horror working day since the 1929 stock market crash.
Suppliers are still pushing metal tea carts along sidewalks with loud clatters and carrying trays loaded with muffins for breakfast sessions.
Latinos are still slouching between apartments, like human pack animals laden with around 50 ironed T-shirts hanging from a yoke-like pole on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for their breakfast bagels at food stalls on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on a weekday.
It didn’t feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon when I decided to open a new savings account due to all the doomsday talk.
Although I had decided to put my duty on the quiet late afternoon at my JP Morgan Chase branch, about 20 people were already in line.
Not at the cash desks to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists for directions to Macy's department store and where new customers open accounts.
Most before me, I later learned from Starr, my “personal licensed bank clerk,” who was standing in line for the same reason I was.
Unlike me, however, they had already taken their savings from smaller banks, in places from where they commuted, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (a bit like a building savings bank), cooperative banks, and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state, saying they treat their customers like family.
In the last year, 15 of these banks have gone quietly bankrupt.
Over the past few days, Washington Mutual, a $327 billion bank with assets, went into bankruptcy management, and when last Friday New Yorkers drove home over the weekend, Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion in savings, was looking for a bailout buyer.
Fearing another collapse, the office and shop assistants standing in front of me took their cash to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank responsible for most of the bailouts on Wall Street.
Quite ordinary New Yorkers have acquired fluent financial Latin in recent weeks.
A woman who spoke on the phone in my local Chinese supermarket referred with such familiarity to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and its emaciated-looking CEO Dick Fuld, as if she were blaspheming about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment block, has strayed from our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my food delivery.
"I now have all my savings in money market funds," she told me after my visit to the bank.
"I changed, I'm not taking any more risks."
Muslim graves desecrated during right-wing slide in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a left-winger of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter, a member of the Belgian right-wing Pertei Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, 17 January 2008, to represent the organisation "Cities against Islamization".
They carry signs in the style of traffic signs on which a mosque is depicted, crossed out with a red line.
The police accuse right-wing extremists of desecration of the grave in a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same weekend at the extreme right parties record significant gains in the parliamentary election of the country.
In the night from Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves in the cemetery in Traun near Linz were seriously damaged in an action, according to police.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols such as the David Stern on some of the graves, but criminal officials consider this an attempt to disguise the motive of the extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is in any way related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were “deeply shaken” by the news of the desecration of the tomb that took place as the religious month of Muslim Ramadan draws to a close.
At the same time, a round of conscience research is pending in Austria after the country slid to the right in yesterday’s parliamentary election.
The FP<0xC3><0x96> and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that received almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law in their election campaign and some of their electoral slogans were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, leader of the FP<0xC3><0x96>, who won 18% of the vote, campaigned for a ban on headscarves and burqas and even expressed his aversion to food that is commonly associated with Islam.
At his last rally in Vienna, he spoke of a “European brotherhood” to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the building of mosques and minarets with the argument that these are political symbols of a continuous Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses conducted immediately after the election, which say that the extreme right is the strongest political bloc in the country, suggest that this new development is based on young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter's International Travel Ban
Gary Glitter, the glam rock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain.
Judges imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities controlling him that he wanted to travel to Spain via France.
Kent police were granted a foreign travel ban last Thursday after they presented the judges with evidence of Glitter’s criminal record for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at the Ashford District Court in Kent, but was represented by the law firm Corker Binning.
A Court spokesman reported: "On Thursday 25 September, Kent police at the Ashford District Court applied for permission to prevent Mr. Paul Glad's foreign travel to France and Spain by 25 March.
Paul Gadd was not personally present."
As required by the Register of Sex Offenders, Glitter, 64, had informed authorities that he wanted to travel abroad.
He must inform the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
He must also notify the police 7 days before his scheduled departure.
Failure to notify the authorities could result in a prison sentence of 5 years.
Police in Kent said they would not discuss individual cases or glitter's possible whereabouts in the country.
A spokesperson for Kent’s police force said: “The police in Kent will do everything necessary to protect children in this country and abroad.”
“In our view, it is easier to control someone who is in the UK because we have a comprehensive system to effectively prevent any potential risks.”
"It is a top concern of Kent police to protect Kent residents and we are working closely together to monitor the behavior of registered sex offenders in the country to minimize any risk that may exist to the population.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abuse of 2 girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released Glitter flew to Bangkok, where he was scheduled to take a flight to London.
But he said he did not feel well and refused to fly to London.
The Thai authorities did not let him through passport control and he flew back and forth to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused him entry and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and border officials insisted that he return to Britain.
Last but not least, he arrived at Terminal 3 in Heathrow on 22 August and stayed there while his lawyer, David Corker, went to the Uxbridge District Court in West London, as Scotland Yard had successfully sought permission to require him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter had previously been incarcerated in the UK for 4 months in 1999 for possession of images of child abuse.
According to the Interior Ministry, Interior Minister Jacqui Smith is reassured and satisfied that Glitter has been prevented from traveling to France and Spain.
