Talk - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained the public’s trust, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
It is known that the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Donation Service were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to draw up guidelines to prevent another catastrophe of this nature.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee at the time whose goal was to develop a new system for managing blood canisters in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood-conservation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood vessels and through working in this field over the next few years, we have regained public trust,” she says, before proudly emphasizing that by early 2008, nearly 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998, tells us.
“And we had not the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we invoked one of the main guidelines of the reports by Krever and Gélineau, according to which one applies exclusion measures if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself through degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999 blood was not taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proven without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of prudence we used makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time when the person became infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not detect it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, you would have to distribute 12 million cans of blood before someone would be infected with HIV.
Because Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 canned blood each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case where HIV was transmitted through a blood canned blood.
I believe that these days you can feel comfortable getting or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health,” says the head of Hema-Quebec.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
Just last year, on the island of Réunion, the Chikungunya virus appeared, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We need to monitor continuously', Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate care in addition to a safe supply.
“The demand is increasing because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also affects the blood donor network, which on average includes only 3% of Quebec’s blood-donating residents.”
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is common are excluded from blood donation for one year.
“With these 3%, we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly, to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,' regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood preserves but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for serious fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, which was formerly considered a biomedical waste, there is blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand annually.
“We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this umbilical cord blood loss program as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it, because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all of Quebec’s hospitals.
