'Moving the course of our last great border in the north': this is the long-term goal that Jean Charest presented yesterday by visual means at the General Assembly of the liberal party of Quebec in Levis, following entirely the guidelines..
During his lecture, a kind of picture mill was projected behind him.
On three huge screens, spectacular images of hydropower plants, mines, Quebec viewed in <0x60>Google Maps', maps, etc.
Great resources as during the election period.
Speaking to the press, the prime minister, by the way, refused to rule out that he would hold the elections this autumn, even if he announced that his schedule was very full.
The “Plan North” is the fourth element of a “vision” that the Prime Minister supposedly has for Quebec, namely that of a “new economic area” that provides for an agreement with France on manpower, an agreement between Canada and Europe, and agreements with Ontario.
Although it has been mentioned frequently in the Prime Minister’s speeches in recent times, the opening of the North – the northern area at the 49th parallel – has never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, limited himself to explaining why the North was “a jewel with enormous potential” but did not mention a date, investment sums or precise priorities for the upcoming projects.
