Letters - A dishonoured country
Mr. Vic Toews, ex-'Justice' minister (which irony) in Harper's cabinet, allowed himself last summer to say about Louise Arbour that she was a 'shame' for Canada.
This woman, who has waged an unending struggle for justice and deserves all our admiration for covering her up with shame, says as much about the people around the prime minister as she does about Stephen Parker himself.
We are dealing here with a government that is the only one from all the countries concerned that has not brought home its compatriot imprisoned in the Guantanamo concentration camp.
A government that doesn’t even take into account that Omar Khadr was still a teenager when the things he was accused of happened.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, breaks its word and allows a child soldier to vegetate in inhumane conditions.
The only one who condescends to a judicial parody to assess the guilt of the defendant.
Let’s remember that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Association of Canadian Lawyers in particular are pleading for Omar Khadr to be brought home so that he can get a fair trial in Canada.
It is precisely this government that closes its eyes to torture: they have little interest in the fact that after so many years of torture, a young adult will certainly be mentally broken forever.
We are not yet aware of this, but we are experiencing an insidious curtailment of our rights, our freedom and our ‘democracy’, this word that Harper constantly carries like a flag in front of him, and which sounds so meaningless from his mouth.
