The shame, Mr. Toews, lies in this renunciation, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice Director General of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the largest gold mining company in the world sought a libel suit of six million against three authors and a small penniless publishing house with the aim of opening a “public transparent debate.”
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of libel suits, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to hold an opinion that is contrary to theirs.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defenses and use very unequal weapons to fight an army of lawyers who are paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles, moreover, is often to ruin the defenders in order to force an amicable settlement that silences the opposing side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to public opinion.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas and not through clubbing.
It would have been enough, then, if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened up a real debate, through which newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent audit teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to have confidence in public opinion, wiping aside petitions and letters in support of Noir Canada’s authors with a hand gesture.
Could Mr Garver explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and disregard the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, in the vice president’s world, this word includes only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a pretty narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand — or doesn’t want to understand — is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because they reject the gold mine’s brutal stance.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the ‘public debate’, Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada in which she asks them to stop using that term...).
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth-finding that is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to research and discuss topics that do not please the rich companies of this world, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she doesn’t want a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to limit this type of unjustified lawsuit.
Rescue for Wall Street – Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, designed to stop the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months, has yet to be adopted by the two chambers of congress.
The main contents are: better control of MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public funds used, new decrees to limit the number of houses seized due to arrears, as well as the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Chamber of Deputies President Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative Senator Judd Gregg, who was present at the negotiations, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress toward an agreement that will be effective on the market,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the Wall Street price crisis,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: If we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos, and turmoil in the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,” Gregg said.
Negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, fearing the effect of another failure on investor sentiment.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who took part in the negotiations only late, were more likely to be in favour of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, especially those intended to allow owners to keep their homes, and those concerning the salaries of senior executives of the state-rescued companies.
“If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain persons, that is not something to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on American television.
When asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied, “I’d like to know the details first, but I hope so.
<0x60>The guiding principles that I have read [show] that this is one thing that we will all have to digest, and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing at all is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan is designed to save taxpayers' money.
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime), before it expanded to other forms of more widespread bonds (PCAA), and eventually resulted in a freeze of financial power and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed the first attempt at settlement last week.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain “toxic” assets of the societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not bought, it is believed to escape the impasse.
To round out the view for everyone in Congress, an order has also been added that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes to recover its capital employed.
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion must be approved by Congress in a re-vote.
In return for his help, Washington receives shares in the supported companies that will pay dividends in the event of profits and that it can sell back when the storm has passed.
The federal government will have the option of halting the attachment procedures regarding the housing tied to the real estate loans affected by this plan, and will also set deadlines for repayment and severance payments paid to the executives of the affected companies.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on him today, and then the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
In fact, more voices were raised against this plan yesterday, both by Republicans and Democrats.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t understand us,” Republican Scott Garett, a member of the Chamber’s financial commission, told his constituents.
“Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of asking taxpayers to pay.’
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, leader of a group in Congress called “the caucus of skeptics,” presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to tell us that we ask Congress not to be pressured and to consider carefully what path to take,” he said.
At the same time, we in Europe were once again shown that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, which is in great difficulty since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US dollars) in the crisis due to the high-risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
“This is not lost money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said.
In order to compensate, we receive a right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households appreciate now that uncertain times are about to dawn.”
During this time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalizing another bank distressed by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including over 41 billion (75.5 billion US dollars) from real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank the British government has had to nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis, after Northern Rock.
Paul Newman (19252008) - Death of a dedicated icon
His beauty with the azure blue eyes was for a long time his trump card, no one would say his weakness.
Had the American actor freed himself from the narcissistic mirror with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His sensitivity, sensibility and obvious talent have probably also kept him away from a position of power that gives birth to the truly terrible monsters.
But what a great endurance runner!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer at his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of his golden years.
He was less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled and for whom he was a kind of rival on the screen for a long time, more careful in his acting, certainly also more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the blowing up of dramaturgical conventions.
Mixed blood often results in wonderful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, the son of a German Jew and a Hungarian mother.
From its European roots, one of the glorious faces of the American dream was to emerge.
Without excessive ego, extreme quality feature.
Because in him was reflected an entire country that was in love with the self-made man, the fighter who was wounded in combat in the Pacific War, who studied acting at Yale in the early 1950s and then visited the Actor's Studio in New York, before he had success at the theater, on television and soon also in the cinema.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also the driver who came second in the 1979 24 Hours of Mans race, and also a sex symbol, even though he lived in a showpiece relationship with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him, the unknown facets of this mysterious, restrained, committed and hypersensitive to the glamour of the show business disappear, whose puzzles will never be solved completely.
A decent man, in the purest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman left cinema lovers reeling this weekend as all his big roles were played on the dark screen of memories.
More than half a century of American cinematic art in constant change is passing by with him.
The charming cowboy from "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid" (1969) comes to mind, and the young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Hot Tin Roof, filmed by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
A much shorter memory (1990) is evoked of his sensitive Mr. Bridge, who in his old age is disturbed by a wedding that did not fulfill all her promises.
There have been so many other Paul Newmans throughout history.
This criminal, stormy, violent and unforgettable boxer Rocky Graziano from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, was reprised after his death and made the Newman really famous in 1956.
This sympathetic crook in the outstanding The Sting, who was awarded the Oscar for Best Film in 1973.
As a bitter and vengeful billiard player in the wonderful The Hustler by Robert Rossen (1961),
That face through the ages, that was him.
Still him.
In his life, epochs unite.
Young people know him from the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, the little orthodox coach of an ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
In 2003, he played the role of the godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes.
Unlike several cinema legends who retired from the film world early enough, Newman was to remain in the saddle for a long time, betraying Hollywood, its fortunes, its pageantry, and its concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier saw him, not without humor, as a living challenge to the ‘underplaying’, when he judged his all-too-expressive performances.
The profession was not always easy for the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles flew for a long time.
However, he rarely played Sunnyboys as an outsider: neurotic, alcoholic, mean-spirited or desperate, with whose perfect presentation he reflected his slipping and rebellion.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown sides of his true sensitive sensibility.
His 1968 Rachel, Rachel (after the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence) with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a subtle female portrait full of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son, a work full of sensitivity and sadness.
His close friend and former comrade in arms Robert Redford (who had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said: “His presence has improved my life and this country.”
Generosity and joie de vivre were essential characteristics of the late actor.
Apart from his legendary career, a great advocate of civil rights, environmental protection and independent cinema, an opponent of Hollywood drift, is now also going to die.
We have often seen him standing with his foot in bowls full of vinaigrette, in sauces, pastries or other foods, and thought this to be quite tasteless, although we found it funny at first.
Nevertheless, the profits from his sales flowed into his foundation for children in need.
Instead of resting on his myth, Newman engaged to the shot.
He left a letter to his five daughters with these words: “Always and until the very end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was an honor to be here.”
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the life of such an intelligent and generous American actor.
An exemplary citizen, in the narrowest and broadest sense.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
