The Psychology of Exceeding – or Why We’re Ready to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves up in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was to play the lottery while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the overtaking of the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore felt that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To substantiate their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally conducted investigations into the tracking of money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was told the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged victorious from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
The only difference between the two groups was that the emphasis was on winning while the emphasis was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the “against losing” gambling group were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or “profit” group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviors observed at auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated to be one hundred thousand in Germany, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in the case of hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as semen, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travellers are advised to vaccinate against viruses A and B in any case, there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from the much more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people infected is on medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, held for the first time in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, its development and the importance of early detection.
