Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand an image of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci’s “Lady with the Hermitage”.
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of religious trance among the faithful while selecting da Vinci’s painting because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt reassuring.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were to look at either the religious or the other painting.
