Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google would be able to answer questions such as "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What job really suits me?", but software programs were not yet able to do this because they did not know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches, the search terms would be registered, as well as the IP addresses from which they were searched, and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search", introduced two years ago, allows the visitor to save his own search history and later access it, so that the hits can be generated much more precisely later, and the same logic is also used to base the so-called "Recommendations", with which the system recommends customized products and services based on the previous preferences.
However, users wonder what happens in the event of data misuse - "If you look at what I do" - some are concerned about the Google data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is more the potential power represented by the company that is frightening, and less the sense of guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or the revolt against the power that is met with rejection by many Internet users.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but are also passed on to third parties in the event of an incident, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent crackdown on paedophilia in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called “Orkut” that also allowed the pedophilia to be identified.
However, users concerned about personal rights were able to breathe a sigh of relief in May, when Google, together with the civil rights organization EFF, successfully went to court against the FBI: according to this, Google can still in the future not be forced with any point of the Constitution to release information to the FBI on secret request.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, but has been deprived of the list of individual users, or their web and search terms list, for two months retroactively.)
So Google’s image remains controversial: those who are reluctant to release their personal data because they fear the loss of their privacy and privacy through the use of Google services are lashing out at the company with the outrage due to the conservative companies.
However, the American “geek culture,” which is present in many countries and unites avid computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of “cool entrepreneurs” in them, as opposed to Microsoft, which is market leader thanks to Windows, even if both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require its users to have identification codes, and provides its services for free, so an open, constantly updated source code and program package seems far more attractive, youthful, and cooler than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks see through the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet in a razor-sharp way - a relationship that has come to the fore especially in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
"Web 2.0" is about nothing more than collaboration, that is, the users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show themselves in public.
An average young person can simultaneously manage their profile on multiple community portals - from Facebook to Xanga, can connect them through other services such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can eventually incorporate all of this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can run blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries posted on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove: When looking at the party photos of the previous night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend was having fun with, or the employee is fired because he is all too honestly venting his anger about company management on his blog - one thing is for sure: The term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Who lives an online life is what he reveals about himself - so one could formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And those who try to keep something secret, or even bypass the Google monopoly, can do so - such as with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine, but deliberately leaves no traces.
Quite a few people deliberately do not register on community pages so that they cannot be found, but also Google’s online applications, such as word processing and graphic tools and RSS feeds, can be handled with alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile from the user.
Public opinion, however, is waiting until Google shows its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), AdWords/AdSense’s advertising space threatens the revenues of advertising agencies, and the ever-faster introduction of services is causing headaches not only for Microsoft but also for other software developers.
Critical observers, however, also find the disturbing opposites: For example, the company management has completely rejected a protest by the employees, after the fees of the company's own kindergarten were doubled, and the management said that the repeated feeding of the employees is too expensive. However, all this would seem to contradict the fact that Google in 2006 was even in the taste before the Chinese government went to the knee and agreed with an agreement.
The internal regulation of the group is that no new service will be advertised in advance, but only if it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could turn things around again a lot: While some think that Google's book and magazine scanning or archiving project is now assuming dimensions that the company would soon have to deal with the Supreme Court of Justice, so others are worried about the situation because of the "health" system.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database is already providing the stuff to the next generation of sci-fi authors - such as "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow describes in the best Orwellian way a future in which a human being becomes frighteningly approachable thanks to data obtained from Google.
