Intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method to develop new technologies for accident prevention, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, in which Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees in creating new accident-avoiding systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval “private area” that is very similar to our own “protective shield,” Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibit.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the compound eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the autorobot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t, the autorobot wouldn’t be able to react fast enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Autorobot project.
The system must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently still considered unavoidable.
The entire process must reflect the behavior of the bees as they dodge other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the dodging cannot take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the manoeuvrability of the tires.
While there are endless possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use rotary motion, or acceleration and deceleration, in the autorobot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes down to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It does not have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so that it requires only a handful of KB of memory on an ongoing basis.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could be the technology in GPS satellite navigation, by deliberately steering the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to his destination.
