This just mentioned example, however, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even already represents: not only in the US, but also in the entire West and perhaps even beyond it will be affected by them.
Both in the States and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-awaited events which are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means a decline in the banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of private households residing in a single state.
This means a direct political problem for the governments: how to deal with the families concerned, which are also an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis therefore appears to be economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have fallen into disrepute and lost its right to speak: the obvious proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its dichotomy in various national and international conflicts, is unable to find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, above all, distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two preconditions that cannot be overstated – under certain circumstances – which no international organization or market will otherwise be able to fall back on in a similar way.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed on the state-national element is in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance recently associated in the economy with a most closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, precisely when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked empire, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we suddenly have to determine how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to another in the world, but they are still connected to the utmost with a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, he who has such a territory has an advantage over another who lives in a cropless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short insertion.
Whoever says territory, whoever says government, whoever says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to manage things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, even more disturbing aspect: a loss of trust, an intolerance, a picture of inadvisability, a sense of distance, all of which is aimed at a whole class of managers in Western countries.
It seems to be the conviction among large sections of the population that it is not first the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content presents itself to the majority as increasingly foreign and traditional.
