The super glue that lets go up on walls
Defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and be able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centers, one of which seems to have almost reached its destination.
With an adhesive applied to an area of only 2.5 square meters, the researchers succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the already used adhesives, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
“The principle of glue can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged into a stack of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
Tests using different materials, such as glass Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the reptile’s feet and at the same time “has no problem removing it from the wall,” said Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton’s Faculty of Engineering.
“This material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” Liming Dai adds.
Maybe, but the researchers are thinking of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could fall into the field of space travel.
So for now, the superheroes still have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH – including the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the Californian scientists present an adhesive made of microfibers that clean themselves from dust like hair by moving on a surface itself, thus always maintaining perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in the summer due to their refreshing quality and richness of vitamins, can cause serious damage to health if taken at the same time with certain vital drugs, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaged and fresh fruit juices in combination with medication. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again raised the alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is all it takes to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to virtually eliminate them and thus endanger the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
Medications in Danger – The same agency of the drug had warned doctors and patients in a report two years ago about the dangers of this mix, stressing to pay attention to what is drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepam or metadon.
IT’S NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Therefore, the appeal of Michele Carruba, Director of the Universit<0xC3><0xA0> Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still ambiguities, not to be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor," emphasizes the expert of the Ansa agency.
Nobel Prize goes to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences is awarded to Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the attacks of September 11, 2001, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times editorial that this second event was more crucial to U.S. history than the attacks.
A prediction that received quite a bit of polemics in response and was still held up to the economist years later, but today proves to be completely correct.
“I’m surprised and shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals surrounding the collapses of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from public view,” Krugman said.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an “economist of great value,” but also a banalizer with a “very aggressive style, particularly against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration.”
Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package appears
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has arrived; the open source software, as a free replacement for Microsoft’s Office, is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, among freelancers as well as in public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office presents itself with some novelties to the public: in addition to a revised and now more Spartan designed initial menu, now finally a fundamentally guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x, as well as the support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version, is given.
Eight against was also the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that makes it possible to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which, for example, makes it easier to send via email, including the ability to import PDF files into graphic editing modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
In this way, "hybrid" PDF files can now also be generated, which extend the typical graphic of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by multiple hands by different users, avoiding conflicts in case of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a question to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are in the process of publishing various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result is to be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus, it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent to your home or office.
However, if cost-free access can be an incentive for the distribution of the program in private households, it is also in the area of business, where OpenOffice could be the big hit: after all, various institutions of public administration and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of a training offer, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized companies, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice is made up of five main components: Writer, the word-appropriate text creation program; Calc, the spreadsheet program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, for creating presentations as with PowerPoint; Dbase for operating databases in place of the more familiar Access; and lastly Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can easily be exceeded with 3 million and 600 thousand already achieved.
