Female students victims of high rents of up to 900 euros per room
The student housing market has no crisis.
According to the latest investigation by Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on a very serious character, and so many students lose their right to study because their families are unable to support them at this level," said Laura Mariani, the head of the Sunia, "in these cities, the high demand from the students leads to a deformation of the market, which has also harmed the other inhabitants.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rent limit, unauthorized sublets.
For Sunia there is a need for extraordinary measures, which lead to lower rental prices through a revision of taxation.
On closer examination of the investigation, it turns out that in Milan a sleeping place in the Brianza district is needed about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a place to sleep costs on average 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a sleeping place of 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a place to sleep in a double room.
