Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historical cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means, in the long run, death for the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the features of a cultural crime.
It’s like losing a friend with whom you’ve walked a street full of emotions,” says the director of the film “Nuovo Cinema Paradiso”, which won him the Oscar and the Cannes Grand Prix 20 years ago. It’s the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a world of cinema that is lost forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak for themselves: in the last five years, the enormous number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; this mine paid for the most part the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also emerge, but first and foremost is the preservation of what already exists, because if a hall in the city closes, not all its regular customers are willing to go to a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here still remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association outside attention: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from an ethical and moral standpoint that the government does not comply with the existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to decide to protect the old cinemas by an agreement between the municipality and Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting the traditional cinemas, both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the measures foreseen are tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-limited areas of the center and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a gratifying initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also develop new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of multiplex rooms, because after all, the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid having to see the dusty posters.
