When the energy comes from the waves, suddenly the big ones come on.
It’s a never-ending source of money covering over 70% of the planet’s surface, and only now do the world’s major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the motions of the sea has been under consideration and studied for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil plummeted around 1980, the idea of ocean energy was gassed, but now environmental organizations and the increased price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be met by the energies generated by ocean waves.
This would be twice the amount of energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are the currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract to build a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are focusing on marine energy production.
“Chevron is exploring these technologies,” said the spokesman for a company known to the giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering the possibility of working with us.”
It is about obtaining an authorization from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a not to be underestimated sign, especially considering that oil continues to be produced by the United States in Alaska and President Bush has only recently initiated plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers speak of increasing interest.
Technologies that need to be improved.
Experts speak of a technology that is still on the rise, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, large-scale energy production requires technologies that have a far greater impact on the environment.
Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this type, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator as a result of the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Production Research, a particular interest is immediately deserving of the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
